00:21:39,103 --> 00:21:41,404
Hello, Pankaj, thank you so much, that was fantastic.

307
00:21:41,905 --> 00:21:45,487
I was just curious if you'd be willing to share any techniques that you like to really

308
00:21:46,288 --> 00:21:51,952
give that lower end ear candy that is great in your mixes, if you have anything that you

309
00:21:51,972 --> 00:21:55,855
particularly enjoy, because obviously just the orchestral samples probably can't produce

310
00:21:55,875 --> 00:21:57,556
that low warmth.

311
00:21:58,097 --> 00:22:00,479
Okay, so we recorded brass and strings live.

312
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:02,761
Sometimes I use a little bit more,

313
00:22:03,261 --> 00:22:05,203
like one more cello or two more celli,

314
00:22:05,603 --> 00:22:08,386
but then the real magic is John Raud sitting right there.

315
00:22:08,486 --> 00:22:09,107
He's fantastic.

316
00:22:09,147 --> 00:22:10,928
He's the one who really shapes that low end.

317
00:22:11,409 --> 00:22:13,911
Because I've worked so much in horror and fantasy,

318
00:22:13,971 --> 00:22:14,912
there is always that.

319
00:22:15,392 --> 00:22:17,253
music competing with the sound effects.

320
00:22:17,433 --> 00:22:20,953
And I had so many conversations with people in horror games

321
00:22:20,973 --> 00:22:23,114
basically saying, that's your biggest goal,

322
00:22:23,174 --> 00:22:25,194
how to shape, how to sculpt the low end

323
00:22:25,254 --> 00:22:27,114
so we still hear the machine guns

324
00:22:27,154 --> 00:22:28,234
and they don't sound like popcorn.

325
00:22:28,795 --> 00:22:30,835
But so that the music really works,

326
00:22:30,855 --> 00:22:34,996
see because all we hear, sound effects, folly, dialogue,

327
00:22:35,116 --> 00:22:36,276
it all goes into the ears.

328
00:22:36,676 --> 00:22:38,576
So the music has to be very carefully sculpted

329
00:22:38,716 --> 00:22:40,317
around the other elements in the audio.

330
00:22:40,377 --> 00:22:42,137
And me coming from a genre background,

331
00:22:42,197 --> 00:22:44,157
having done a lot of horror films and a lot of my music.

332
00:22:44,417 --> 00:22:50,467
having been cut and not used. I learned the hard way to be incredibly sensitive, but talk to John,

333
00:22:50,507 --> 00:22:54,233
he's going to give you the magic, the actual technicality. I just write the music, the notes.

334
00:22:54,699 --> 00:22:57,441
But it starts with you putting in the musical elements.

335
00:22:57,461 --> 00:22:59,824
Do you have any particular nice combinations?

336
00:23:00,124 --> 00:23:03,147
I have ways, I have a really specific way how I voice the brass.

337
00:23:03,247 --> 00:23:05,910
I always use octaves, two octaves, sometimes three octaves.

338
00:23:06,991 --> 00:23:11,056
I worked for many years for the orchestrator of Hans Zimmer,

339
00:23:11,076 --> 00:23:12,717
called Bruce Fowler, and he taught me how

340
00:23:12,757 --> 00:23:15,320
to add one extra lower octave in the tuba.

341
00:23:15,921 --> 00:23:19,543
So I have a particular way how I voice the brass that's just really heavy, like really punchy,

342
00:23:19,624 --> 00:23:22,466
and it really kind of shows in all my orchestrations for Steve Jablonski.

343
00:23:23,246 --> 00:23:26,169
Same thing with the strings, just really beef up the low end in octaves,

344
00:23:26,569 --> 00:23:28,591
but never like in anything less than an octave.

345
00:23:28,631 --> 00:23:31,953
So in the composition, in the arrangement, that's what I do, just kind of beef it up.

346
00:23:32,534 --> 00:23:33,074
Awesome, thank you.

347
00:23:33,254 --> 00:23:33,615
Thank you.

348
00:23:35,176 --> 00:23:39,980
Hi, so for the developer who may or may not be somewhat musically inclined,

349
00:23:41,185 --> 00:23:46,269
Do you have a sense of that you prefer to have direction from them in non-musical terms

350
00:23:46,329 --> 00:23:52,615
like timid, warm, you know, sensual, or that you would actually, to what degree are you

351
00:23:52,655 --> 00:23:55,618
open to very specific, like I want this to be an oboe?

352
00:23:57,022 --> 00:23:58,683
Thank you, this is a perfect, awesome question.

353
00:23:58,723 --> 00:23:59,263
Thank you so much.

354
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:02,885
The best collaborative process is if the developers

355
00:24:03,105 --> 00:24:05,486
speak with their composers in terms of ideas.

356
00:24:05,746 --> 00:24:07,287
First, talk to us about ideas.

357
00:24:07,327 --> 00:24:09,788
Talk to us about emotions, mechanics,

358
00:24:10,108 --> 00:24:12,149
storytelling, tradition, innovation.

359
00:24:12,649 --> 00:24:15,550
The large, big concepts, so that's the one aspect

360
00:24:15,610 --> 00:24:16,650
of wonderful collaboration.

361
00:24:16,691 --> 00:24:17,831
The other collaboration is music.

362
00:24:17,851 --> 00:24:19,632
Just give us like five MP3s and say,

363
00:24:19,672 --> 00:24:20,532
well, I really love this.

364
00:24:21,092 --> 00:24:22,833
Follow, you know, I like this about this,

365
00:24:22,973 --> 00:24:24,194
I don't like this about this other thing.

366
00:24:24,634 --> 00:24:26,455
So when we have both the concepts.

367
00:24:26,934 --> 00:24:32,117
and the music equally represented music in terms of style guide from previous games or movies.

368
00:24:32,578 --> 00:24:35,459
This is just the best because we know your concepts and your vision,

369
00:24:35,800 --> 00:24:40,222
but we also know the kind of music that speaks to you and you feel is going to represent your game.

370
00:24:40,763 --> 00:24:45,666
So if you only talk to us in words, then words are slippery.

371
00:24:45,766 --> 00:24:48,988
I mean, we could talk about music and I'd say one thing, you interpret.

372
00:24:49,028 --> 00:24:50,789
So there could be this misunderstanding.

373
00:24:51,189 --> 00:24:54,111
But when it's the sense of concepts and aesthetics and ideas,

374
00:24:54,671 --> 00:24:58,396
Also reinforced by your favorite music that you feel is gonna fit with the game.

375
00:24:59,037 --> 00:25:03,123
That company, the company that made Mayhem, they did give me two mp3s.

376
00:25:03,583 --> 00:25:04,625
They said this is what we like.

377
00:25:06,006 --> 00:25:07,929
Make it like this, but unique for our game.

378
00:25:08,816 --> 00:25:13,940
So I would say the best collaborative approach is ideas and your favorite music combined together.

379
00:25:14,260 --> 00:25:20,424
And then the composers, they have ways of filtering, they have intuition and just skills and experience to filter.

380
00:25:21,024 --> 00:25:27,728
And also, all of us, I encourage all composers to just play as many games, watch as many movies, learn the genres, learn music,

381
00:25:27,809 --> 00:25:30,590
because that kind of becomes part of your intelligence as a composer.

382
00:25:31,351 --> 00:25:35,493
I just voraciously play games and watch games all the time, so that's what we do.

383
00:25:36,394 --> 00:25:36,994
But I would say...

384
00:25:37,535 --> 00:25:38,715
concepts and music.

385
00:25:39,756 --> 00:25:39,936
Yes.

386
00:25:40,216 --> 00:25:43,518
Hi. I was wondering for the Gemini 8 piece,

387
00:25:44,779 --> 00:25:50,382
how, or do you have a process for going from the general timeline

388
00:25:51,203 --> 00:25:55,345
of the presentation of the film and the,

389
00:25:56,206 --> 00:25:59,647
to the specifics of like tempo, things like that,

390
00:25:59,728 --> 00:26:03,710
like does the overall length of the piece help determine your tempo?

391
00:26:03,810 --> 00:26:05,311
Do you set that independently?

392
00:26:06,230 --> 00:26:07,591
motivically, the structure?

393
00:26:07,611 --> 00:26:09,212
So that's a really good question.

394
00:26:09,373 --> 00:26:12,315
So the entire 3D movie is with dialogue.

395
00:26:12,375 --> 00:26:13,856
So all the music was under dialogue.

396
00:26:14,297 --> 00:26:15,878
And all the three, because it's like a documentary,

397
00:26:15,898 --> 00:26:17,840
essentially, except it's really elaborate

398
00:26:17,880 --> 00:26:19,461
with special effects, which you didn't see here.

399
00:26:20,182 --> 00:26:22,484
So that's one of my first assignments,

400
00:26:22,544 --> 00:26:23,405
and it's very challenging.

401
00:26:23,485 --> 00:26:24,906
People ask me what's the happiest

402
00:26:24,966 --> 00:26:26,327
and most challenging part.

403
00:26:26,367 --> 00:26:28,449
The happiest part is these conceptual conversations

404
00:26:28,489 --> 00:26:29,490
I just spoke about.

405
00:26:29,730 --> 00:26:30,291
They're the funnest.

406
00:26:30,731 --> 00:26:32,273
research and concepts is awesome.

407
00:26:32,794 --> 00:26:35,156
The hardest part is when I open the blank template

408
00:26:35,597 --> 00:26:37,139
and the movie's there, it's lined up,

409
00:26:37,559 --> 00:26:39,742
and my job is to pace the music,

410
00:26:40,062 --> 00:26:41,283
really structure the music,

411
00:26:41,343 --> 00:26:43,426
so I always begin globally, that's how I work.

412
00:26:43,766 --> 00:26:45,548
Not everybody's like this, that's just my process.

413
00:26:46,029 --> 00:26:48,211
I would kind of mark the movie,

414
00:26:48,552 --> 00:26:49,913
remember that chart I had with the...

415
00:26:50,817 --> 00:26:53,118
energy curve kind of going up, so I had to sort of...

416
00:26:53,638 --> 00:26:55,159
And then you have to hit beats.

417
00:26:55,359 --> 00:26:58,320
In any linear media, which cinematics in games are,

418
00:26:58,480 --> 00:27:00,781
or film scoring, or this 3D entertainment,

419
00:27:01,241 --> 00:27:02,842
it's linear media, so we have to hit

420
00:27:04,043 --> 00:27:07,144
moments where the energy changes, or the story changes.

421
00:27:07,824 --> 00:27:10,185
So that's the first thing I do, and it's challenging,

422
00:27:10,726 --> 00:27:12,206
because I haven't set the tempos yet,

423
00:27:12,226 --> 00:27:14,167
and sometimes I have to lock these markers,

424
00:27:14,207 --> 00:27:16,828
so I lock the markers, and then I experiment

425
00:27:16,848 --> 00:27:19,430
with different tempos until I find the right tempo.

426
00:27:20,383 --> 00:27:20,703
Thank you.

427
00:27:21,003 --> 00:27:21,323
Thank you.

